WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.040 --> 00:00:00.260
Hello.

2
00:00:01.340 --> 00:00:01.960
Good afternoon.

3
00:00:02.800 --> 00:00:06.120
My name is Alvaro Monteiro from Moffitt Cancer Center.

4
00:00:06.180 --> 00:00:10.160
I'm going to chair this session on identification

5
00:00:10.210 --> 00:00:13.860
and management of reduced penetrance high-risk cancer gene

6
00:00:13.980 --> 00:00:16.919
variants. And there will be three talks.

7
00:00:18.600 --> 00:00:18.980
One

8
00:00:19.880 --> 00:00:23.800
started by Dr. Tuva Pal from Vanderbilt, then followed

9
00:00:23.840 --> 00:00:27.360
by a talk by myself on functional

10
00:00:27.420 --> 00:00:31.300
analysis, and then Dr. Bryson Catona will finish

11
00:00:31.320 --> 00:00:32.701
that up as well.

12
00:00:33.540 --> 00:00:37.440
So the way it is organized right now is that each of the

13
00:00:37.480 --> 00:00:41.080
talks will be 20 minutes. We have a nine-to-10 minutes

14
00:00:41.100 --> 00:00:44.480
discussion as well. But I think one

15
00:00:44.560 --> 00:00:48.080
possibility is that because all the talks are interrelated,

16
00:00:48.900 --> 00:00:52.800
we may have less questions after each one, and then at the end

17
00:00:52.860 --> 00:00:56.140
we have a broader discussion that may be easier

18
00:00:56.860 --> 00:00:58.980
for everyone to participate as well.

19
00:01:00.620 --> 00:01:04.340
I think the learning objectives for today is really to evaluate

20
00:01:04.420 --> 00:01:06.480
inherited cancer risk as a continuum.

21
00:01:06.860 --> 00:01:08.940
I think really this is the key here.

22
00:01:09.450 --> 00:01:13.300
And recognize the limitations of this binary variant classification,

23
00:01:13.740 --> 00:01:17.240
particularly for these reduced penetrance pathogenic variants.

24
00:01:18.400 --> 00:01:21.960
Another one is really to interpret, or give some

25
00:01:21.980 --> 00:01:25.740
framework to interpret the functional and clinical evidence, which

26
00:01:25.820 --> 00:01:29.360
includes some multiplex assays of variant effects, or MAVEs,

27
00:01:30.540 --> 00:01:34.440
to identify and classify these reduced penetrance pathogenic variants.

28
00:01:34.520 --> 00:01:38.130
And finally, to understand risk-adapted screening and

29
00:01:38.220 --> 00:01:41.940
prevention strategies for individuals with reduced penetrance

30
00:01:42.020 --> 00:01:45.660
variants in hereditary cancer syndromes, including Lynch syndrome

31
00:01:46.080 --> 00:01:49.980
and APC-associated conditions. And the idea

32
00:01:50.180 --> 00:01:53.860
is that this is really a subject in flow, so

33
00:01:54.200 --> 00:01:56.040
every opinion is very welcome.

34
00:01:56.880 --> 00:02:00.740
So we even have doubts about nomenclature and how we

35
00:02:00.780 --> 00:02:04.580
should call different things, so we welcome comments

36
00:02:04.800 --> 00:02:05.280
as well.

37
00:02:07.040 --> 00:02:10.539
I think we'll start with Dr. Pal. Please.

38
00:02:11.080 --> 00:02:11.500
Thank you.

39
00:02:17.600 --> 00:02:21.500
Okay. Thank you, Alvaro, for the kind introduction, and the organizers

40
00:02:21.580 --> 00:02:24.940
for inviting me to speak at this session.

41
00:02:24.980 --> 00:02:28.010
So like Alvaro already said, I'm going to be talking about consideration of

42
00:02:28.040 --> 00:02:31.860
inherited cancer risk on a continuum and really set the

43
00:02:31.980 --> 00:02:35.320
stage for some of the other talks as well from a clinical standpoint.

44
00:02:36.660 --> 00:02:39.720
So again, really what we're talking about is

45
00:02:39.780 --> 00:02:43.280
shifting our mindset from a binary

46
00:02:43.380 --> 00:02:45.840
framework to a continuous framework.

47
00:02:46.100 --> 00:02:49.520
And we published on this through a Points to Consider

48
00:02:49.620 --> 00:02:50.100
paper

49
00:02:51.060 --> 00:02:54.280
in "Genetics in Medicine" a few months ago.

50
00:02:54.400 --> 00:02:58.240
And really, I'm using a lot of that paper to

51
00:02:58.280 --> 00:02:59.420
frame my talk. I

52
00:03:02.600 --> 00:03:06.560
want to put in my acknowledgements right away because, again, what I'm talking

53
00:03:06.620 --> 00:03:10.040
about is not just something I thought about, but it was

54
00:03:11.360 --> 00:03:14.940
colleagues across the US and beyond, including our

55
00:03:15.420 --> 00:03:18.980
eminent Dr. Monteiro, who are on the work group to really think

56
00:03:19.040 --> 00:03:19.840
this through.

57
00:03:21.800 --> 00:03:25.420
So just using historical context and using the

58
00:03:25.480 --> 00:03:29.280
BRCA genes as an example. In the 1990s, when

59
00:03:29.440 --> 00:03:33.230
there were studies of multi-generational, highly penetrant families,

60
00:03:33.600 --> 00:03:37.340
that's what led to the discovery of the BRCA1 and BRCA2 genes.

61
00:03:38.840 --> 00:03:42.340
So it made sense to have a binary framework because

62
00:03:42.760 --> 00:03:46.560
there was such a high risk of cancer

63
00:03:46.660 --> 00:03:49.980
with presence of a germline mutation.

64
00:03:51.500 --> 00:03:53.960
But over time, I'd say the lines have become blurred.

65
00:03:54.240 --> 00:03:56.260
And this is a family that we saw in our clinic.

66
00:03:56.920 --> 00:04:00.820
The original woman that got tested was

67
00:04:00.880 --> 00:04:04.680
an 84-year-old with metastatic breast cancer, which prompted the

68
00:04:04.740 --> 00:04:08.280
testing that identified a BRCA2 mutation.

69
00:04:08.700 --> 00:04:12.160
Subsequently, her two daughters got tested. They're in their 50s.

70
00:04:12.410 --> 00:04:14.710
They're unaffected, but they're positive.

71
00:04:14.860 --> 00:04:18.360
And then the granddaughter is who I saw, 28-year-old, also

72
00:04:18.380 --> 00:04:18.899
positive.

73
00:04:20.380 --> 00:04:23.300
Now, this is a paper that we published late in

74
00:04:23.480 --> 00:04:26.870
2024, and really it was

75
00:04:26.900 --> 00:04:29.980
compiling a list of 16 consensus

76
00:04:30.060 --> 00:04:33.800
variants in BRCA1 and BRCA2 that were classified

77
00:04:33.900 --> 00:04:37.600
as reduced penetrance across two labs, Myriad and Ambry.

78
00:04:38.120 --> 00:04:41.940
And this was work that was done in collaboration with those labs, as well as many

79
00:04:41.980 --> 00:04:45.300
colleagues, including Dr. Alvaro Monteiro and Dr.

80
00:04:45.500 --> 00:04:46.140
Fergus Couch.

81
00:04:46.980 --> 00:04:50.960
And you can see the one I circle is one of the variants for that

82
00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:52.340
family that I just mentioned.

83
00:04:53.400 --> 00:04:56.820
Now, we look in ClinVar, and you see that it says

84
00:04:56.860 --> 00:05:00.160
pathogenic, which again, doesn't tip off

85
00:05:00.760 --> 00:05:04.740
the individual looking this up that there's something a little

86
00:05:04.780 --> 00:05:06.340
bit different about this variant.

87
00:05:07.620 --> 00:05:11.480
And then buried in one of the entries, you see it may be

88
00:05:11.520 --> 00:05:14.080
hypomorphic, may present with reduced risk.

89
00:05:14.140 --> 00:05:18.060
So again, my point here is that these are not always easy

90
00:05:18.460 --> 00:05:19.220
to identify.

91
00:05:21.440 --> 00:05:25.300
Now, this same variant was seen in another one of our families in our

92
00:05:25.340 --> 00:05:29.230
clinic. And here you see 45-year-old unaffected woman,

93
00:05:29.600 --> 00:05:33.340
but in the maternal lineage, which is where it's coming from, there are

94
00:05:33.480 --> 00:05:37.400
multiple cases of breast cancer, some of which are early, and they

95
00:05:37.480 --> 00:05:38.950
track with the

96
00:05:39.020 --> 00:05:42.620
BRCA2 positivity.

97
00:05:42.940 --> 00:05:46.860
So again, my point in saying this is, this doesn't look like

98
00:05:46.900 --> 00:05:48.580
a moderate penetrance variant, right?

99
00:05:48.900 --> 00:05:52.420
But this, again, reinforces the point that

100
00:05:52.940 --> 00:05:56.280
even if it is reduced penetrance, we still have to look at what we're seeing

101
00:05:56.720 --> 00:06:00.539
clinically with the patient. So the family history definitely still needs to be

102
00:06:00.580 --> 00:06:04.304
taken into account.So going

103
00:06:04.384 --> 00:06:08.374
into classification systems, this was

104
00:06:08.404 --> 00:06:08.954
published

105
00:06:10.224 --> 00:06:13.824
over a decade ago, the ACMG guidelines for variant

106
00:06:13.844 --> 00:06:17.464
interpretation. And really it gives us three big

107
00:06:17.524 --> 00:06:21.124
categories. We have the benign, likely benigns, which are generally

108
00:06:21.224 --> 00:06:25.104
negative, the VUS category, and then the likely pathogenic,

109
00:06:25.204 --> 00:06:27.984
pathogenic, which is generally what we think of as positive.

110
00:06:28.564 --> 00:06:32.104
And it's important to remember that these guidelines were designed for

111
00:06:32.244 --> 00:06:33.924
highly penetrant variants.

112
00:06:35.884 --> 00:06:39.364
In contrast, there have been more recent guidelines

113
00:06:39.964 --> 00:06:43.824
or recommendations through CANVIG UK that better account

114
00:06:43.864 --> 00:06:47.544
for the spectrum of risk. And that's important to really think

115
00:06:47.604 --> 00:06:51.564
about because this VUS category is better

116
00:06:51.584 --> 00:06:55.284
divided with this. And again, what we see

117
00:06:55.384 --> 00:06:59.364
is that some of these hot VUSs are the ones that are

118
00:06:59.404 --> 00:07:02.224
the discrepant results in ClinVar.

119
00:07:03.184 --> 00:07:05.444
I am told that there is an update in progress.

120
00:07:05.504 --> 00:07:09.494
We've been hearing this for a while, but hopefully it'll be published later

121
00:07:09.524 --> 00:07:11.444
this year through ACMG.

122
00:07:15.004 --> 00:07:18.824
So here we have another family again that we saw in

123
00:07:18.904 --> 00:07:19.304
clinic.

124
00:07:20.144 --> 00:07:24.124
61-year-old female that I saw. Age 46, she had ER

125
00:07:24.164 --> 00:07:26.364
positive breast cancer on the right side.

126
00:07:26.784 --> 00:07:30.564
And then at age 61, she had triple negative breast cancer on the left

127
00:07:30.664 --> 00:07:34.004
side. And genetic testing identified this

128
00:07:34.044 --> 00:07:35.844
BRCA2 VUS.

129
00:07:38.384 --> 00:07:40.454
You look at the ClinVar entry.

130
00:07:41.824 --> 00:07:43.404
Eight labs called it a VUS.

131
00:07:44.204 --> 00:07:47.044
Six labs called it pathogenic, likely pathogenic.

132
00:07:47.564 --> 00:07:51.504
So again, this kind of raises the possibility, is

133
00:07:51.564 --> 00:07:53.244
this a reduced penetrance variant?

134
00:07:53.724 --> 00:07:57.454
And again, I don't have all the answers for this, but these are things

135
00:07:57.704 --> 00:08:01.664
that we really think about when we're thinking about,

136
00:08:01.784 --> 00:08:05.624
well, what are the strategies to approach these

137
00:08:05.664 --> 00:08:09.414
discrepant results in clinic? What is the impact of counseling?

138
00:08:09.464 --> 00:08:11.603
Because it definitely impacts our counseling.

139
00:08:11.684 --> 00:08:14.214
And then the impact on cancer risk management.

140
00:08:14.504 --> 00:08:16.884
And again, we really need to be thoughtful about that as well.

141
00:08:19.384 --> 00:08:23.044
So another family, 24-year-old, referred for

142
00:08:23.144 --> 00:08:26.084
risk assessment and testing. So this one's interesting.

143
00:08:26.124 --> 00:08:29.904
The mom was the one who was diagnosed with stage three ovarian cancer,

144
00:08:30.884 --> 00:08:34.444
tested through LabOne. So she was RAD51D positive,

145
00:08:34.824 --> 00:08:36.965
which is an ovarian cancer predisposing gene.

146
00:08:37.374 --> 00:08:41.184
And then she had this BRCA2 VUS. The proband

147
00:08:41.444 --> 00:08:45.024
was tested many years later appropriately because she was very young

148
00:08:45.064 --> 00:08:48.984
when the mom was tested. She was tested in her mid-20s, and

149
00:08:49.044 --> 00:08:53.034
she had the same BRCA2 variant, but it

150
00:08:53.104 --> 00:08:56.984
was interpreted as pathogenic. So again, two family

151
00:08:57.064 --> 00:09:00.624
members that are getting the same variant identified through two

152
00:09:00.724 --> 00:09:02.724
labs with different interpretations.

153
00:09:04.624 --> 00:09:08.524
So when we look at the ClinVar entry, it's interpreted as pathogenic,

154
00:09:09.084 --> 00:09:09.624
but then

155
00:09:11.124 --> 00:09:14.124
buried in one of the entries, it says it may be hypomorphic.

156
00:09:14.184 --> 00:09:15.884
So again, when we see these

157
00:09:17.324 --> 00:09:18.474
discrepant results,

158
00:09:19.624 --> 00:09:23.334
it may be hypomorphic. In this case, there were no discrepant results

159
00:09:23.544 --> 00:09:26.254
because the other lab had not yet

160
00:09:27.384 --> 00:09:29.184
inputted the information into ClinVar.

161
00:09:31.104 --> 00:09:35.064
So when we're thinking about considerations, the patient interface, the family

162
00:09:35.144 --> 00:09:38.424
member tested at different labs with discordant

163
00:09:38.464 --> 00:09:41.964
interpretations of the same variant does pose

164
00:09:42.024 --> 00:09:45.864
challenges, and we need to be thoughtful as we approach our patients with this kind

165
00:09:45.904 --> 00:09:49.864
of information. When we're thinking about the mother with ovarian cancer and

166
00:09:49.904 --> 00:09:53.184
the RAD51D positivity with the patient being

167
00:09:53.244 --> 00:09:56.124
RAD51D negative, but both having the

168
00:09:56.164 --> 00:09:59.964
BRCA2 positive result, which is likely a

169
00:09:59.984 --> 00:10:03.764
hypomorph, does this impact what we tell our patient

170
00:10:04.104 --> 00:10:05.784
sitting in front of us who's in her mid-20s?

171
00:10:06.164 --> 00:10:09.714
And right now I would say no it doesn't because we don't have

172
00:10:09.784 --> 00:10:13.704
evidence that the risk for ovarian cancer is such that we

173
00:10:13.724 --> 00:10:16.524
wouldn't make a strong recommendation for risk-reducing

174
00:10:16.594 --> 00:10:18.424
salpingooophorectomy

175
00:10:19.404 --> 00:10:20.124
at a later age.

176
00:10:21.983 --> 00:10:25.804
Recommendations for breast cancer risk management, I don't think it really

177
00:10:25.844 --> 00:10:29.764
impacts breast screening. We would still recommend the breast MRI.

178
00:10:30.144 --> 00:10:33.384
It really comes down in my mind to shared

179
00:10:33.404 --> 00:10:36.744
decision-making regarding the risk-reducing mastectomy.

180
00:10:37.214 --> 00:10:41.084
Again, the patient may decide to take this information into account to

181
00:10:41.124 --> 00:10:44.224
either delay or forgo risk-reducing mastectomy, but I think

182
00:10:44.324 --> 00:10:46.504
it behooves a discussion.

183
00:10:49.584 --> 00:10:51.924
And then now I wanted to get to terminology.

184
00:10:52.324 --> 00:10:55.724
So when we're looking at currently available terminology in

185
00:10:55.764 --> 00:10:59.044
ClinVar, we have these two categories.

186
00:10:59.104 --> 00:11:02.444
They're likely pathogenic low penetrance and

187
00:11:02.564 --> 00:11:06.464
pathogenic low penetrance. Now, we've

188
00:11:06.504 --> 00:11:10.264
had discussions and with the labs, they're worried that this low

189
00:11:10.404 --> 00:11:13.704
penetrance suggests it's lower than population

190
00:11:14.844 --> 00:11:17.344
risk, which is not what this is supposed to reflect.

191
00:11:17.864 --> 00:11:19.264
So again,

192
00:11:20.104 --> 00:11:23.404
at a national and international level, some of the consensus

193
00:11:24.084 --> 00:11:27.704
groups have suggested reduced penetrance instead of low

194
00:11:27.764 --> 00:11:30.554
penetrance, which seems to be more palatable to the labs.

195
00:11:30.964 --> 00:11:32.834
It is something that

196
00:11:33.764 --> 00:11:37.304
we've been having ongoing discussions about, and my hope is that it

197
00:11:37.344 --> 00:11:40.904
changes. I think from a clinical standpoint, what would be

198
00:11:40.964 --> 00:11:44.824
nice is just to have some sort of terminology that

199
00:11:44.884 --> 00:11:46.104
tells us we need to

200
00:11:46.964 --> 00:11:49.424
dig deeper when we see variants in ClinVar.

201
00:11:49.774 --> 00:11:53.284
And right now I think that is missing in many of these cases.

202
00:11:54.944 --> 00:11:58.344
So just going back to terminology, I've been kind of

203
00:11:59.204 --> 00:12:02.804
using hypomorph and reduced penetrance pathogenic variant interchangeably,

204
00:12:03.184 --> 00:12:06.924
but they are different. So with hypomorph, that refers to the gene

205
00:12:06.984 --> 00:12:10.614
function.Whereas RPPV refers to the

206
00:12:10.664 --> 00:12:13.664
resulting risk, so the actual clinical relevance.

207
00:12:14.124 --> 00:12:15.784
And those two things are not the same.

208
00:12:17.864 --> 00:12:21.654
So again, there have been a lot of functional studies,

209
00:12:21.664 --> 00:12:25.604
both led by Doctors Fergus Couch and Alvaro Montero, that are

210
00:12:25.624 --> 00:12:29.224
really trying to figure out functionally what are these variants doing.

211
00:12:29.884 --> 00:12:33.084
In parallel, there's a study that's being led

212
00:12:33.664 --> 00:12:37.264
by my colleague, Dr. Brian Shirts, who's trying to

213
00:12:37.324 --> 00:12:40.524
estimate variant specific risks in BRCA1 and

214
00:12:40.564 --> 00:12:44.404
BRCA2, reduced penetrance pathogenic variants, through building out

215
00:12:44.504 --> 00:12:47.984
pedigrees and testing families, so segregation analysis.

216
00:12:48.374 --> 00:12:51.124
And what he's doing through this is

217
00:12:52.944 --> 00:12:56.813
offering family members free ancestry testing, which is optional, as well

218
00:12:56.824 --> 00:13:00.224
as free genetic testing through Dr. Mary-Claire King's lab.

219
00:13:04.264 --> 00:13:07.953
Now, beyond BRCA, there are other

220
00:13:09.504 --> 00:13:11.784
genetic conditions where we also see these

221
00:13:12.684 --> 00:13:14.384
genotype/phenotype correlations.

222
00:13:14.464 --> 00:13:18.454
So with Li-Fraumeni syndrome, we've known for a long time there's

223
00:13:18.504 --> 00:13:21.404
quite a spectrum of risks. Now,

224
00:13:22.864 --> 00:13:26.804
this again is a family that I saw in clinic, and I follow many

225
00:13:26.864 --> 00:13:30.744
of these family members that are positive with total body MRIs.

226
00:13:30.764 --> 00:13:34.684
And what you see here is there's two women with early onset

227
00:13:34.724 --> 00:13:38.664
breast cancer, their dad with prostate cancer at age

228
00:13:38.904 --> 00:13:42.864
50. And again, doesn't look super

229
00:13:43.264 --> 00:13:47.124
reflective of a low penetrance variant, but that is

230
00:13:47.184 --> 00:13:49.784
kind of what is reported in the literature.

231
00:13:50.684 --> 00:13:54.164
I'd been doing the total body MRIs, and then my

232
00:13:54.244 --> 00:13:54.784
patient

233
00:13:55.704 --> 00:13:59.024
developed a uterine sarcoma in between with mets to the lung.

234
00:13:59.104 --> 00:14:02.664
So again, these are not necessarily families

235
00:14:03.044 --> 00:14:05.444
that we can pull back screening on.

236
00:14:05.564 --> 00:14:09.424
So it poses challenges because we know they don't look typical for

237
00:14:09.504 --> 00:14:09.624
a

238
00:14:10.464 --> 00:14:14.384
Li-Fraumeni syndrome family, but does reduced penetrance

239
00:14:14.504 --> 00:14:18.464
really mean reduced penetrance in childhood, or is there

240
00:14:18.504 --> 00:14:21.884
penetrance later on in life? And I think those are questions

241
00:14:21.944 --> 00:14:23.604
that still need to be answered.

242
00:14:24.684 --> 00:14:28.234
So when we look at the ClinVar interpretation, back in 2023,

243
00:14:28.664 --> 00:14:31.524
it said conflicting interpretation, but more

244
00:14:31.544 --> 00:14:34.434
recently, it's saying likely pathogenic.

245
00:14:34.664 --> 00:14:37.624
So labs do update this information over time.

246
00:14:37.664 --> 00:14:40.844
But with Lab 1 said, "But do not meet

247
00:14:40.924 --> 00:14:44.364
Li-Fraumeni syndrome criteria, potentially an attenuated

248
00:14:44.424 --> 00:14:47.704
phenotype." Lab 2 said, "Risk limited to breast cancer."

249
00:14:48.144 --> 00:14:50.824
Neither of which are things that we are seeing in our family.

250
00:14:50.944 --> 00:14:52.844
So again, more to be done here.

251
00:14:54.644 --> 00:14:58.544
So going back to shifting to consider risks on a continuum, like I

252
00:14:58.624 --> 00:15:02.604
was mentioning before, the risk continuum is based on interactions between

253
00:15:02.684 --> 00:15:06.424
multiple different factors. We're talking about

254
00:15:06.544 --> 00:15:10.004
gene, variant, polygenic risk score, as well as modifying factors.

255
00:15:10.094 --> 00:15:14.064
And the risk contribution varies across genes, is dynamic

256
00:15:14.104 --> 00:15:16.324
across the lifetime, which is really important to remember.

257
00:15:16.764 --> 00:15:19.604
And the penetrance is organ specific as well as age related.

258
00:15:21.144 --> 00:15:25.054
So when we're thinking about established breast cancer genes, there were

259
00:15:25.084 --> 00:15:28.624
two studies that were published towards the end or in

260
00:15:28.784 --> 00:15:32.354
2021 in the New England Journal of

261
00:15:32.424 --> 00:15:36.214
Medicine. The Bridges study, which was over 100,000 women from

262
00:15:36.344 --> 00:15:39.884
25 countries, as well as a carrier study, over

263
00:15:40.044 --> 00:15:43.944
60,000 women in the US. And the bottom line here is they

264
00:15:43.984 --> 00:15:47.944
showed very similar findings in terms of the genes and in

265
00:15:48.044 --> 00:15:51.434
terms of the risk. So this, I would say, is the best data we have

266
00:15:51.904 --> 00:15:55.204
thus far to tell us these are the main genes.

267
00:15:55.224 --> 00:15:57.544
There are other genes as well, but these are the main ones.

268
00:15:58.744 --> 00:16:02.524
Now, when we think of penetrance estimates, we think of gene,

269
00:16:02.784 --> 00:16:05.824
but we're now also starting to think about variant.

270
00:16:06.104 --> 00:16:09.824
We already talked about BRCA RPPVs, but there

271
00:16:09.924 --> 00:16:13.824
is a BRCA1 variant specifically that...

272
00:16:14.844 --> 00:16:18.814
So if we think of BRCA1, we think of it as one of the hereditary breast

273
00:16:18.924 --> 00:16:20.304
cancer high penetrance genes.

274
00:16:21.764 --> 00:16:25.763
But this R1699Q variant is one

275
00:16:25.823 --> 00:16:29.144
of those BRCA1 variants that has enough of a

276
00:16:29.164 --> 00:16:32.964
population frequency for us to generate variant specific

277
00:16:33.004 --> 00:16:36.284
risk. And it falls in the moderate penetrance range very

278
00:16:36.324 --> 00:16:39.864
clearly. It's in the mid-20s in terms of lifetime risk.

279
00:16:40.964 --> 00:16:43.564
CHEK2, our favorite variant, the

280
00:16:43.664 --> 00:16:47.494
I157T, has an odds ratio of 1.2,

281
00:16:47.684 --> 00:16:51.304
1.3-ish, so well below the lifetime risk

282
00:16:51.864 --> 00:16:53.884
of 20% for breast cancer.

283
00:16:54.804 --> 00:16:58.664
And then we have the ATM 2424G, which

284
00:16:58.784 --> 00:17:02.744
is a variant that imparts the lifetime risk

285
00:17:02.764 --> 00:17:04.884
of breast cancer in the range of about 60%.

286
00:17:05.184 --> 00:17:07.404
So again, what I'm trying to

287
00:17:08.545 --> 00:17:12.484
say here is that even though penetrance estimates

288
00:17:12.504 --> 00:17:15.585
are anchored to genes, I think we're getting closer

289
00:17:15.704 --> 00:17:19.444
to certain times being able to anchor them in addition to

290
00:17:19.484 --> 00:17:22.384
variants, and those variants may actually change

291
00:17:22.464 --> 00:17:25.384
categories for the risk that we think of

292
00:17:26.464 --> 00:17:27.444
on a clinical basis.

293
00:17:29.004 --> 00:17:32.904
So when we're thinking about variant classification, we tend to think of

294
00:17:32.984 --> 00:17:36.914
negative, VUS, and positive. And really what we're thinking

295
00:17:36.984 --> 00:17:40.644
now is, yes, we have negative VUS, but maybe there should be an

296
00:17:40.784 --> 00:17:43.984
intermediate positive and a highly positive

297
00:17:44.584 --> 00:17:44.924
group.

298
00:17:47.024 --> 00:17:49.424
And then when we get back to the NCCN guidelines,

299
00:17:51.064 --> 00:17:55.024
these variants are not obvious in the NCCN guidelines, but they are in

300
00:17:55.064 --> 00:17:58.044
there. They're in there as footnotes at this point.

301
00:17:58.204 --> 00:18:00.414
I am hopeful that we'll be able to change the structure

302
00:18:01.564 --> 00:18:03.604
such that they're easier to identify.

303
00:18:04.164 --> 00:18:08.144
But again, as this list grows, we just need strategies to figure

304
00:18:08.224 --> 00:18:10.484
out how we are going to share it with the

305
00:18:10.504 --> 00:18:14.090
communityNow going back

306
00:18:14.160 --> 00:18:17.680
to polygenic risk score, which is another level of

307
00:18:17.720 --> 00:18:20.900
information that we can sometimes get.

308
00:18:21.020 --> 00:18:24.460
When we're thinking about lifetime risk of breast cancer anchored

309
00:18:24.500 --> 00:18:28.180
at 20%, if a woman has a breast cancer

310
00:18:28.220 --> 00:18:31.960
risk of 20% or higher, they generally are

311
00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:35.360
recommended to have a breast MRI. Now, when we

312
00:18:35.460 --> 00:18:38.980
overlay polygenic risk scores over the

313
00:18:40.020 --> 00:18:43.420
gene mutation status, it's really the moderate penetrance

314
00:18:43.540 --> 00:18:47.410
genes that are the most impacted. So in

315
00:18:47.460 --> 00:18:51.440
this study, which was again based on the carrier study, about a

316
00:18:51.460 --> 00:18:55.320
third of CHEK2 and half of ATM carriers when you

317
00:18:55.360 --> 00:18:59.250
incorporated the polygenic risk score that did

318
00:18:59.400 --> 00:19:03.040
not reach the threshold of 20% lifetime risk of breast

319
00:19:03.080 --> 00:19:06.560
cancer. In contrast, you see BRCA1 and BRCA2

320
00:19:07.020 --> 00:19:10.620
are well to the right, so it doesn't impact risk

321
00:19:10.700 --> 00:19:11.940
management as much for them.

322
00:19:12.900 --> 00:19:16.630
So the impact of PRS is mainly on moderate penetrance genes,

323
00:19:16.940 --> 00:19:17.360
but then

324
00:19:18.160 --> 00:19:21.940
one of the things is the BRCA reduced penetrance pathogenic

325
00:19:22.020 --> 00:19:24.330
variants are moderate penetrance genes.

326
00:19:24.650 --> 00:19:26.160
So what is going to happen with them?

327
00:19:26.200 --> 00:19:30.160
We don't have any studies at this point that overlay

328
00:19:30.560 --> 00:19:32.620
PRS on them. So more to come on that.

329
00:19:34.640 --> 00:19:38.460
Now going into the wider genetic context and other

330
00:19:38.500 --> 00:19:42.420
modifiers, there was a study that was published late last year.

331
00:19:42.520 --> 00:19:46.470
I found it interesting because it looked at hereditary breast cancer genes and then

332
00:19:46.500 --> 00:19:49.930
the impact of family history of breast cancer, as well as additional

333
00:19:49.960 --> 00:19:53.240
non-genetic risk factors. And what they found is

334
00:19:53.340 --> 00:19:56.180
that the influence varied by gene.

335
00:19:56.240 --> 00:20:00.000
So in my mind, this is additional data that would be nice to

336
00:20:00.040 --> 00:20:03.720
incorporate into the risk models to refine the risks that we're giving our

337
00:20:03.760 --> 00:20:04.220
patients.

338
00:20:06.260 --> 00:20:09.930
And when we're thinking about why breast cancer risk is important and

339
00:20:09.940 --> 00:20:13.740
refining the risk, it's really determining the risk that then tells us

340
00:20:13.860 --> 00:20:17.200
what the management should be. Because with moderate risk, we

341
00:20:17.260 --> 00:20:21.020
recommend the breast MRIs, whereas with high risk,

342
00:20:21.140 --> 00:20:25.120
that's really we reserve the risk-reducing mastectomies in the high-risk

343
00:20:25.220 --> 00:20:25.450
group.

344
00:20:27.420 --> 00:20:31.190
So our goal is to personalize risk, and that

345
00:20:31.260 --> 00:20:35.020
entails multiple levels of data, and there are

346
00:20:35.060 --> 00:20:38.920
risk models to model these risks. There's CANrisk and

347
00:20:38.980 --> 00:20:42.700
Tyrer-Cuzick that incorporate gene mutation status, but

348
00:20:42.720 --> 00:20:46.680
really CANrisk is the one that incorporates multiple

349
00:20:46.800 --> 00:20:49.500
genes as well as PRS at this point.

350
00:20:50.640 --> 00:20:54.360
So CANrisk is an online tool, and it does

351
00:20:54.520 --> 00:20:57.420
incorporate these various risk

352
00:20:57.520 --> 00:21:01.380
factors to generate a score for both breast cancer as well as

353
00:21:01.420 --> 00:21:02.200
ovarian cancer.

354
00:21:03.420 --> 00:21:07.060
Then this is just the portal. What you get is a five-year and

355
00:21:07.140 --> 00:21:09.360
ten-year risk, as well as a lifetime risk.

356
00:21:09.580 --> 00:21:13.220
The thing is, the five and ten-year risks are much better in terms

357
00:21:13.300 --> 00:21:15.560
of accuracy than the lifetime risk.

358
00:21:15.920 --> 00:21:18.200
So this model does

359
00:21:19.160 --> 00:21:23.150
all of them. But again, when we're talking to patients, we have to remember

360
00:21:23.150 --> 00:21:26.880
is all models are wrong, but some are useful, and that's how I think of CANrisk.

361
00:21:26.960 --> 00:21:30.549
Because at the end of the day, we're giving them an exact point estimate, but we're

362
00:21:30.620 --> 00:21:33.380
not that good. There's a confidence interval around that.

363
00:21:33.820 --> 00:21:37.540
So the way I think about it is, it gives me an idea of, are

364
00:21:37.620 --> 00:21:41.440
they higher than what I would expect a certain gene carrier to be or

365
00:21:41.480 --> 00:21:42.240
lower? So

366
00:21:43.200 --> 00:21:47.040
it gives us an idea of what the next steps could be, and really it

367
00:21:47.080 --> 00:21:48.739
comes down to shared decision-making.

368
00:21:49.100 --> 00:21:52.820
And what's exciting is CANrisk version four was recently released and now

369
00:21:52.860 --> 00:21:54.160
includes prostate cancer.

370
00:21:55.760 --> 00:21:59.280
So here's another patient, 42-year-old unaffected female,

371
00:21:59.780 --> 00:22:03.610
tested positive for ATM, and when we ran her CANrisk, it was

372
00:22:03.660 --> 00:22:05.680
about a 30% lifetime risk.

373
00:22:06.700 --> 00:22:10.410
And when we look at this risk in the

374
00:22:10.460 --> 00:22:14.420
context of PRS, again, you see going from

375
00:22:15.960 --> 00:22:19.800
just under 30% to over 40%. When we incorporate dense

376
00:22:19.900 --> 00:22:23.500
breasts, it's mid 30, like 35% risk or so.

377
00:22:23.820 --> 00:22:27.780
So again, you can see how additional data gives us additional

378
00:22:27.880 --> 00:22:29.200
refinement of risks.

379
00:22:30.060 --> 00:22:33.640
So when we're thinking about thresholds based on genotype, genomic

380
00:22:33.700 --> 00:22:37.560
context, and other factors, really, I think we're going to

381
00:22:37.640 --> 00:22:41.480
have to take all of these into account as we figure

382
00:22:41.560 --> 00:22:45.100
out what the risks are. So just as an example, with intermediate

383
00:22:45.200 --> 00:22:47.930
risk GPVs, if you

384
00:22:48.060 --> 00:22:51.960
have more risk factors for genomic context and

385
00:22:52.000 --> 00:22:55.980
other factors, it may put you in the high-risk category versus if you don't

386
00:22:56.040 --> 00:22:56.480
have it.

387
00:22:58.560 --> 00:23:01.800
And then with risk refinement and precision over time,

388
00:23:02.500 --> 00:23:05.920
my hope is that we're just going to have smaller and smaller buckets

389
00:23:06.400 --> 00:23:10.240
of risk. Again, I don't think we're ever going to be able to give an exact point

390
00:23:10.300 --> 00:23:12.860
estimate, but we'll get better than where we're at right now.

391
00:23:14.120 --> 00:23:17.940
So what's becoming evident is risk refinement is increasingly complex.

392
00:23:18.320 --> 00:23:20.300
Communication strategies will be critical.

393
00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:24.500
So in summary, cancer risks are on a continuum rather than

394
00:23:24.560 --> 00:23:26.600
positive versus negative, which is, I think,

395
00:23:27.580 --> 00:23:31.380
too simplistic nowadays. Genotype-phenotype associations

396
00:23:31.460 --> 00:23:35.100
can change risk categories, and we're trying to figure out how that might

397
00:23:35.180 --> 00:23:39.030
influence care. And then other genetic and non-genetic risk factors

398
00:23:39.100 --> 00:23:40.400
may also influence risk.

399
00:23:41.460 --> 00:23:45.180
So again, this is complicated information

400
00:23:45.260 --> 00:23:47.700
to keep up with. We do have resources.

401
00:23:48.120 --> 00:23:49.380
I think there are resources

402
00:23:50.600 --> 00:23:53.340
broadly available, but we host this inherited cancer registry.

403
00:23:53.380 --> 00:23:56.460
If anyone's interested, I have some of the resources there.

404
00:23:56.520 --> 00:24:00.030
I just put this slide up because we do host case conferences once a month.

405
00:24:00.460 --> 00:24:03.020
Dr. Monteiro is our guest expert in a few weeks.

