00:45:24.518 --> 00:45:27.718
variants, suggesting that these regions of the

756
00:45:27.738 --> 00:45:31.538
proteins are really sensitive and changes

757
00:45:31.558 --> 00:45:35.498
may lead to a complete loss of activity, but they may

758
00:45:35.618 --> 00:45:39.498
also lead to a partial

759
00:45:39.538 --> 00:45:40.718
reduction in function.

760
00:45:41.898 --> 00:45:45.278
So can we use functional analysis to identify these variants?

761
00:45:45.698 --> 00:45:46.497
Yes, we can.

762
00:45:47.498 --> 00:45:51.438
But the question is, which of these functions are we looking at,

763
00:45:51.538 --> 00:45:55.118
right? So as far as we're trying to predict

764
00:45:55.178 --> 00:45:58.858
pathogenicity, as long as a functional assay

765
00:45:59.378 --> 00:46:03.118
has high sensitivity and specificity, it may be

766
00:46:03.918 --> 00:46:07.738
tangentially related to the actual molecular function as

767
00:46:07.798 --> 00:46:11.438
long as it's a good predictor. However, if now

768
00:46:11.578 --> 00:46:15.478
we're doing a slightly different thing, which is to try to

769
00:46:15.538 --> 00:46:19.118
point out which of these variants are going to be a reduced

770
00:46:19.218 --> 00:46:23.118
penetrance, we need to figure out exactly which

771
00:46:23.218 --> 00:46:26.298
functions are actually leading to cancer risk.

772
00:46:26.438 --> 00:46:28.918
And this is not really trivial.

773
00:46:30.838 --> 00:46:34.778
So one of the approach that we're pursuing right now

774
00:46:34.998 --> 00:46:38.778
is really to try to establish the relationship

775
00:46:38.818 --> 00:46:42.658
between these hypomorphic variants and the reduced penetrance

776
00:46:43.138 --> 00:46:46.918
pathogenic variants in which we do a functional assay.

777
00:46:46.978 --> 00:46:50.638
For example, we identify the variants that are in this

778
00:46:50.898 --> 00:46:54.798
intermediate range, and then we look whether they

779
00:46:54.838 --> 00:46:57.878
are validated, for example, in additional assays.

780
00:46:58.458 --> 00:47:01.858
And then we go out and try to estimate their

781
00:47:01.878 --> 00:47:05.838
penetrance so that we can now identify at least

782
00:47:05.898 --> 00:47:09.738
a few of them that can act as anchors

783
00:47:09.837 --> 00:47:13.258
for us. Right? So the idea is demonstrated

784
00:47:13.338 --> 00:47:17.118
here in which we have variants with

785
00:47:17.218 --> 00:47:17.878
high risk,

786
00:47:18.838 --> 00:47:22.758
variants with low risk, and we're trying to correlate that

787
00:47:22.798 --> 00:47:25.818
with low activity and high activity.

788
00:47:26.298 --> 00:47:29.678
But the question is, how do we

789
00:47:29.878 --> 00:47:33.438
decide on the

790
00:47:33.478 --> 00:47:37.128
thresholds? And that's why, as of today,

791
00:47:37.358 --> 00:47:40.578
what we have is that we may have some of these misclassified

792
00:47:40.618 --> 00:47:44.298
variants because we don't have a good handle on

793
00:47:44.378 --> 00:47:47.878
how we adjust the thresholds from risk into

794
00:47:47.938 --> 00:47:51.718
activity. And that's what we call calibration, and if we're

795
00:47:51.798 --> 00:47:55.138
able to use at least a few of these variants

796
00:47:56.338 --> 00:47:59.648
that can be demonstrated in functional analysis,

797
00:48:00.118 --> 00:48:04.078
validated in risk analysis, and then they can ask as a

798
00:48:04.158 --> 00:48:08.138
way to adjust these thresholds, then now we

799
00:48:08.198 --> 00:48:11.838
can go out and have a much larger

800
00:48:11.898 --> 00:48:15.758
scale identification of these variants that can then

801
00:48:15.818 --> 00:48:19.578
be used to apply for clinical recommendations.

802
00:48:20.358 --> 00:48:20.558
So

803
00:48:21.398 --> 00:48:24.818
again, just summarizing here, the idea is that we're going to

804
00:48:25.218 --> 00:48:28.458
go from what it is today, this

805
00:48:28.538 --> 00:48:32.178
binary of pathogenic, likely pathogenic versus

806
00:48:32.238 --> 00:48:36.038
likely benign or benign, into something that is a little bit more

807
00:48:36.078 --> 00:48:39.578
granular. That, for example, now we have a

808
00:48:39.598 --> 00:48:43.318
pathogenic high risk and pathogenic intermediate, and that may

809
00:48:43.398 --> 00:48:45.848
lead to different clinical recommendations.

810
00:48:45.938 --> 00:48:49.738
For example, you can imagine that a variant

811
00:48:49.838 --> 00:48:53.622
that is pathogenicMay still trigger recommendations for

812
00:48:54.002 --> 00:48:57.882
enhanced screening and MRI for breast cancer, but you would not

813
00:48:58.022 --> 00:49:01.922
offer prophylactic surgery for these patients, for example.

814
00:49:02.372 --> 00:49:06.322
And then eventually we can go in and start building on

815
00:49:06.402 --> 00:49:10.222
that model to have better ways of risk

816
00:49:10.262 --> 00:49:14.142
assessment and clinical management of these patients.

817
00:49:14.242 --> 00:49:17.872
And at the very end, I'd like really to leave you with this

