00:54:13.302 --> 00:54:17.142
penetrance variants in Lynch syndrome, and then talk about some of the

899
00:54:17.202 --> 00:54:20.582
management challenges when you cannot use a phenotype-directed

900
00:54:21.042 --> 00:54:21.982
management approach.

901
00:54:23.742 --> 00:54:27.702
All right. So when you have a patient who's at increased cancer risk due

902
00:54:27.742 --> 00:54:31.412
to a genetic predisposition, when you think about developing a

903
00:54:31.442 --> 00:54:35.082
plan for their risk management, there's many factors that are going to contribute

904
00:54:35.142 --> 00:54:39.062
to that, including what is the actual cancer risk associated with the

905
00:54:39.082 --> 00:54:42.822
variant that they carry? What are the screening and/or potential

906
00:54:42.862 --> 00:54:46.822
surgical options that this individual may be eligible for because

907
00:54:46.862 --> 00:54:47.542
of this risk?

908
00:54:48.762 --> 00:54:52.702
How and when should this management be incorporated

909
00:54:52.782 --> 00:54:56.442
into their care? And of course, with any screening or surgical

910
00:54:56.522 --> 00:54:59.942
options, you have to think about what are the risks of those screening

911
00:55:00.442 --> 00:55:04.402
tools and/or surgeries, and are those risks that the

912
00:55:04.462 --> 00:55:04.962
patient

913
00:55:05.862 --> 00:55:09.702
will be willing to take. But there are many other challenges that arise

914
00:55:09.742 --> 00:55:13.642
here. So as has been highlighted earlier, there is a lack of

915
00:55:13.682 --> 00:55:17.122
robust variant-specific risk data to help us make these

916
00:55:17.422 --> 00:55:20.442
decisions. There are differing lab classifications.

917
00:55:21.242 --> 00:55:24.902
A lot of our guidelines don't necessarily address the reduced

918
00:55:24.942 --> 00:55:28.890
penetrance variants, althoughAs Tuo pointed out, the NCCN

919
00:55:28.950 --> 00:55:32.230
is doing a much better job at that, especially in the breast

920
00:55:32.270 --> 00:55:36.250
guidelines. Sometimes patients that carry these variants get mixed

