00:55:36.290 --> 00:55:39.990
messages between providers, and it's also very difficult

922
00:55:40.090 --> 00:55:43.750
to communicate this type of reduced risk to a patient.

923
00:55:44.170 --> 00:55:47.830
So if you see a patient, especially if they have lower health literacy, and you

924
00:55:47.930 --> 00:55:51.550
tell them, "You are on the lower end of a high-risk spectrum," they're going to

925
00:55:51.590 --> 00:55:53.310
have no idea what you're talking about.

926
00:55:54.190 --> 00:55:57.480
And then, of course, I think for these reduced penetrance variants, there's also

927
00:55:57.480 --> 00:56:01.440
a very high risk of overmanagement of

928
00:56:01.490 --> 00:56:02.070
the risk.

929
00:56:03.550 --> 00:56:06.450
So let's go through a couple different examples about how you can think about

930
00:56:06.470 --> 00:56:10.430
different screening tests and risk management strategies for someone who is

931
00:56:10.470 --> 00:56:12.330
a reduced penetrance variant carrier.

932
00:56:12.830 --> 00:56:16.510
So when you think about non-invasive screening tests, so mammograms, PSAs,

933
00:56:16.570 --> 00:56:20.500
things like that, if you have somebody who carries a reduced penetrance

934
00:56:20.570 --> 00:56:24.470
variant, you have to ask, well, is this non-invasive screening test even

935
00:56:24.530 --> 00:56:25.979
needed at all for this individual?

936
00:56:26.450 --> 00:56:30.370
And if it is, do you need to start this potentially at a later age, or

