00:58:23.170 --> 00:58:26.970
debate with all patients who carry hereditary cancer predisposition.

967
00:58:27.430 --> 00:58:27.690
But

968
00:58:28.550 --> 00:58:32.470
may certainly have to be addressed in more detail with those who are

969
00:58:32.550 --> 00:58:35.070
carrying reduced penetrance variants.

970
00:58:36.790 --> 00:58:40.670
All right. So I want to move on to talk a little bit about FAP.

971
00:58:41.830 --> 00:58:45.650
So just to level set a little bit for those who may not live in the GI genetics

972
00:58:45.730 --> 00:58:49.630
world, FAP or familial adenomatous polyposis is

973
00:58:49.670 --> 00:58:53.450
the most common hereditary polyposis syndrome and the

974
00:58:53.490 --> 00:58:57.330
second most common cause of hereditary colorectal cancer following Lynch

975
00:58:57.350 --> 00:59:00.990
syndrome. It's caused by pathogenic variants in the

976
00:59:01.030 --> 00:59:04.470
APC gene. And we have two different forms of

977
00:59:04.910 --> 00:59:07.910
FAP. We have classic FAP and attenuated FAP.

978
00:59:08.410 --> 00:59:11.810
So I think this is actually the ideal condition in my mind to think about

979
00:59:11.870 --> 00:59:15.690
management of reduced penetrance variants, because classic FAP

980
00:59:15.750 --> 00:59:19.240
basically results from high-risk variants, and

981
00:59:19.270 --> 00:59:23.230
attenuated FAP basically results from reduced penetrance variants

982
00:59:23.310 --> 00:59:27.190
in APC. So between the two, classic

983
00:59:27.270 --> 00:59:30.930
FAP are the individuals where they're developing hundreds to thousands of

984
00:59:31.230 --> 00:59:34.830
colorectal polyps over their lifetime, typically starting in the teenage years

985
00:59:35.230 --> 00:59:39.090
with a near 100% risk of developing colorectal cancer if they

986
00:59:39.130 --> 00:59:42.450
don't have some sort of preventive approaches taken.

987
00:59:43.030 --> 00:59:46.170
Whereas attenuated FAP, they develop fewer polyps.

988
00:59:46.330 --> 00:59:48.650
These polyps develop later in life.

989
00:59:49.450 --> 00:59:52.370
And if colorectal cancer develops, usually it's at a later

990
00:59:52.890 --> 00:59:53.510
onset.

991
00:59:55.290 --> 00:59:59.090
Now, FAP is not just a syndrome that impacts the colon.

992
00:59:59.150 --> 01:00:01.570
It also impacts many other areas throughout the body.

993
01:00:02.090 --> 01:00:05.970
Within the luminal GI tract, these individuals are at risk for upper GI

994
01:00:06.070 --> 01:00:09.810
polyps, including polyps in the stomach, both fundic gland polyps and gastric

995
01:00:09.910 --> 01:00:13.830
adenomas, as well as polyps in the duodenum, which you can see here

996
01:00:13.870 --> 01:00:17.250
on the picture on the right, where they can develop duodenal and

997
01:00:17.390 --> 01:00:21.130
ampullary adenomas and certainly have an increased risk of both gastric

998
01:00:21.190 --> 01:00:24.890
cancer and duodenal and ampullary adenocarcinoma.

999
01:00:26.230 --> 01:00:29.620
They develop tumors outside the digestive tract, including desmoid tumors and

1000
01:00:29.690 --> 01:00:33.570
papillary thyroid cancers, and they have many other manifestations

1001
01:00:34.230 --> 01:00:37.230
as well, including CHRPE, which is a

1002
01:00:37.290 --> 01:00:41.270
finding that's found in the back of

1003
01:00:41.310 --> 01:00:44.430
the retina. It's often picked up incidentally.

1004
01:00:45.670 --> 01:00:49.510
Now, the neat thing about FAP is that there is a

1005
01:00:49.550 --> 01:00:53.130
very, very strong genotype-phenotype correlation.

1006
01:00:53.790 --> 01:00:57.670
And so the APC gene is a large gene, has over 2,800

1007
01:00:57.710 --> 01:01:01.570
codons. What we know is that where the mutation occurs

1008
01:01:01.650 --> 01:01:05.590
in the gene really is very predictive of what the phenotype will be

1009
01:01:05.630 --> 01:01:09.490
for these individuals. With the most severe phenotypes

1010
01:01:09.530 --> 01:01:13.220
being these genes in the beta-catenin binding domain of

1011
01:01:13.290 --> 01:01:17.170
APC, whereas individuals who have mutations in the five-prime

1012
01:01:17.270 --> 01:01:20.910
end or in the three-prime end, having a much more attenuated or

1013
01:01:20.970 --> 01:01:23.390
reduced penetrance version of

1014
01:01:23.530 --> 01:01:27.506
FAP.Importantly, a lot of the other manifestations

1015
01:01:27.606 --> 01:01:31.546
outside of colorectal polyps also follow this genotype-phenotype

1016
01:01:31.606 --> 01:01:35.586
correlation. For example, desmoid tumors here are primarily seen

1017
01:01:35.626 --> 01:01:37.346
in individuals who have more 3'

1018
01:01:38.246 --> 01:01:39.926
shifted mutations.

1019
01:01:40.726 --> 01:01:44.526
And this really holds true. So if we think about this particular

1020
01:01:44.586 --> 01:01:46.726
APC variant here that impacts

1021
01:01:48.906 --> 01:01:52.366
the 5' end of the gene, this is one of the more common

1022
01:01:52.726 --> 01:01:56.416
attenuated FAP variants in the United States and is often being

1023
01:01:56.666 --> 01:01:59.986
called an American founder, but it really does have a very

1024
01:02:00.026 --> 01:02:02.326
attenuated polyposis phenotype.

1025
01:02:02.946 --> 01:02:06.306
Whereas opposed to this particular variant here that impacts the

1026
01:02:06.526 --> 01:02:10.506
1309 codon, which is really a hotspot for developing the most profuse

1027
01:02:10.586 --> 01:02:13.256
polyposis, this particular gene has a very

1028
01:02:14.906 --> 01:02:15.446
dramatic

1029
01:02:16.506 --> 01:02:20.046
phenotype, where affected individuals are often needing

1030
01:02:20.346 --> 01:02:22.106
colectomy prior to age 20.

1031
01:02:23.746 --> 01:02:27.546
But what's nice about having this genotype-phenotype correlation

1032
01:02:28.486 --> 01:02:32.126
is that we can use the phenotype to direct our

1033
01:02:32.446 --> 01:02:36.126
management for FAP. And so if you have a reduced

1034
01:02:36.206 --> 01:02:36.486
risk

1035
01:02:37.346 --> 01:02:40.806
variant or reduced penetrance variant in FAP, you're

1036
01:02:40.846 --> 01:02:44.486
basically using the polyp phenotype to

1037
01:02:44.546 --> 01:02:47.826
determine how you manage that particular individual.

1038
01:02:48.606 --> 01:02:52.226
So when we think about upper GI polyp management in FAP,

1039
01:02:52.326 --> 01:02:56.026
specifically in the duodenum, what we follow is something called the

1040
01:02:56.146 --> 01:02:59.726
Spiegelman score, which takes into account the number of polyps an

1041
01:02:59.766 --> 01:03:03.566
individual with FAP has in the duodenum, as well as the size of these

1042
01:03:03.606 --> 01:03:05.896
polyps and some histologic features.

1043
01:03:07.066 --> 01:03:10.686
And we use that Spiegelman score to get a Spiegelman stage.

1044
01:03:11.366 --> 01:03:14.986
So if you have a score of zero, basically meaning that you don't have any duodenal

1045
01:03:15.026 --> 01:03:18.946
polyps, that gives you a Spiegelman stage of zero and

1046
01:03:19.046 --> 01:03:22.886
leads to an upper endoscopy follow-up interval of somewhere between three to

1047
01:03:22.926 --> 01:03:26.786
five years. If you have a Spiegelman stage of one,

1048
01:03:26.866 --> 01:03:30.386
meaning you probably have a couple small polyps in the duodenum, that

1049
01:03:30.446 --> 01:03:33.426
surveillance interval goes down a little bit to two to three years.

1050
01:03:33.966 --> 01:03:37.615
A Spiegelman stage II, you tell these patients to get an upper

1051
01:03:37.626 --> 01:03:41.526
endoscopy every one to two years. Spiegelman stage III, it's every six to 12

1052
01:03:41.606 --> 01:03:45.566
months. And when you get to a Spiegelman stage IV, you're doing very short interval

1053
01:03:45.626 --> 01:03:48.886
upper endoscopy or you're sending these patients for surgery.

1054
01:03:49.666 --> 01:03:53.106
And so this is very nice because if you have a reduced penetrance

1055
01:03:53.966 --> 01:03:57.386
APC variant, you're basically managing the upper GI

1056
01:03:57.566 --> 01:04:00.266
tract based on what the polyp burden looks like.

1057
01:04:00.276 --> 01:04:03.636
And so management in this case, again, when it's phenotype directive, is

1058
01:04:03.846 --> 01:04:05.826
very easy to do.

1059
01:04:07.386 --> 01:04:11.266
We similarly do this for colorectal polyp management in

1060
01:04:11.366 --> 01:04:12.326
FAP as well.

1061
01:04:13.126 --> 01:04:16.306
In classical FAP, individuals will typically start

1062
01:04:16.346 --> 01:04:20.256
colonoscopy somewhere between age 10 to 15, and

1063
01:04:20.366 --> 01:04:24.206
people with classical FAP basically will need a colectomy at

1064
01:04:24.266 --> 01:04:27.106
some point because they're developing thousands of polyps.

1065
01:04:27.126 --> 01:04:30.166
The question is, when will that colectomy be needed?

1066
01:04:30.206 --> 01:04:34.126
And so we start colonoscopy between age 10 to 15 and repeat

1067
01:04:34.186 --> 01:04:37.966
this yearly until the polyp burden is increasing to a

1068
01:04:38.126 --> 01:04:41.026
point where we think, okay, colectomy is needed.

1069
01:04:42.246 --> 01:04:45.986
Now, in attenuated FAP, patients start colonoscopy a little bit

1070
01:04:46.046 --> 01:04:49.966
later, but again, we use the phenotype of the colons to direct

1071
01:04:50.006 --> 01:04:53.206
how frequently or how we should manage that colorectal polyp burden.

1072
01:04:53.806 --> 01:04:57.336
So if they have minimal polyp burden, maybe they can get away with getting a

1073
01:04:57.366 --> 01:05:01.316
colonoscopy every two years. If they have an endoscopically, we'll

1074
01:05:01.386 --> 01:05:03.886
say manageable polyp burden, because manageable

1075
01:05:03.966 --> 01:05:07.666
has a different definition for every gastroenterologist.

1076
01:05:08.506 --> 01:05:12.306
But if you can handle the polyps every year, they may be getting a colonoscopy

1077
01:05:12.346 --> 01:05:15.735
every one year. And for some of these patients, eventually they may need to go on

1078
01:05:15.806 --> 01:05:17.866
to colectomy because of a high polyp burden.

1079
01:05:17.926 --> 01:05:21.626
But again, really focusing on the fact that because we have a phenotype

1080
01:05:22.026 --> 01:05:25.566
that is basically directly proportional to the risk, we can use that

1081
01:05:25.606 --> 01:05:27.246
phenotype to guide management,

1082
01:05:28.146 --> 01:05:31.126
which is incredibly important for these reduced penetrance variants.

1083
01:05:32.886 --> 01:05:36.786
Now I want to switch gears to Lynch syndrome, because in Lynch syndrome,

1084
01:05:37.326 --> 01:05:40.726
when thinking about managing reduced penetrance variants, we do not have that

1085
01:05:41.026 --> 01:05:44.886
phenotype to help us, and so it becomes a little bit more difficult.

1086
01:05:45.546 --> 01:05:48.026
So let me just level set a little bit for Lynch syndrome.

1087
01:05:48.286 --> 01:05:51.806
Lynch syndrome is the most common hereditary colorectal cancer syndrome,

1088
01:05:52.286 --> 01:05:54.566
impacting about one in 300 individuals.

1089
01:05:54.606 --> 01:05:58.546
It's actually more common than having a BRCA1 or 2 mutation, which I think a lot

1090
01:05:58.586 --> 01:06:00.286
of people don't realize.

1091
01:06:01.166 --> 01:06:04.186
There are five different genes that are associated with Lynch syndrome, and these

1092
01:06:04.226 --> 01:06:07.186
genes impact the mismatch repair system.

1093
01:06:07.806 --> 01:06:11.346
And there are many different cancers where risk is increased in Lynch syndrome.

1094
01:06:11.446 --> 01:06:15.346
Colorectal and endometrial cancer have the highest risk, but there are

1095
01:06:15.406 --> 01:06:19.206
other digestive tract cancers such as gastric cancer, small intestinal cancer, and

1096
01:06:19.286 --> 01:06:21.246
pancreatic cancer, where risk is increased.

1097
01:06:21.866 --> 01:06:25.826
There's other cancers outside of the digestive tract too, such as urinary

1098
01:06:25.866 --> 01:06:29.626
tract cancer, ovarian cancer, prostate cancer, and sebaceous

1099
01:06:29.666 --> 01:06:32.586
skin cancer, where risk is increased as well.

1100
01:06:34.866 --> 01:06:38.806
Now, thinking about Lynch syndrome more broadly, before we get into specific

1101
01:06:38.906 --> 01:06:40.696
reduced penetrance variants.

1102
01:06:41.646 --> 01:06:45.586
When we manage cancer risk in Lynch syndrome, kind of a baseline,

1103
01:06:45.666 --> 01:06:49.626
we use a gene specific approach. And so let's think about

1104
01:06:49.666 --> 01:06:52.466
this for colorectal cancer surveillance in Lynch syndrome.

1105
01:06:53.046 --> 01:06:56.926
Looking at cumulative colon cancer risk data, what you can see

1106
01:06:56.966 --> 01:07:00.606
here is that carriers of an MLH1 or MSH2 mutation

1107
01:07:00.666 --> 01:07:04.306
clearly have higher risks of colorectal cancer, and that risk starts to

1108
01:07:04.346 --> 01:07:07.676
increase at younger ages compared to MSH6 and

1109
01:07:07.706 --> 01:07:11.376
PMS2 carriers. Because of that, we adjust how

1110
01:07:11.446 --> 01:07:14.116
we implement screening in these individuals.

1111
01:07:14.146 --> 01:07:18.126
So for these higher risk genes, we're starting colonoscopy somewhere between age

1112
01:07:18.266 --> 01:07:21.786
20 to 25, and we're repeating colonoscopy every one to two

1113
01:07:21.846 --> 01:07:23.386
years. But for the

1114
01:07:24.306 --> 01:07:27.846
lower penetrance MSH6 and PMS2 genes, we're starting

1115
01:07:27.886 --> 01:07:31.466
colonoscopy a little bit later, between 30 to 35, and repeating

1116
01:07:31.506 --> 01:07:34.506
colonoscopy potentially up to every three years.

1117
01:07:34.526 --> 01:07:38.366
So we're using the gene in this case to drive the

1118
01:07:38.406 --> 01:07:40.126
cancer risk management strategies.

1119
01:07:40.896 --> 01:07:44.606
A similar approach is used for gynecologic cancer risk

1120
01:07:44.666 --> 01:07:48.450
management.And specifically, we'll talk about endometrial cancer

1121
01:07:48.850 --> 01:07:50.210
risk management in Lynch syndrome.

1122
01:07:50.630 --> 01:07:53.930
And what you can see here is that for endometrial cancer, there's a big difference

1123
01:07:53.990 --> 01:07:57.630
with PMS2 being a remarkably reduced penetrant

1124
01:07:58.070 --> 01:08:00.610
gene compared to all the other genes in Lynch syndrome.

1125
01:08:01.110 --> 01:08:05.050
Overall risk of endometrial cancer is lower, and the age

1126
01:08:05.090 --> 01:08:07.240
of onset of endometrial cancer is later.

1127
01:08:07.870 --> 01:08:11.520
And so because of that, we then optimize or utilize this,

1128
01:08:12.450 --> 01:08:15.950
which the gene that the patient carries, to determine how their

1129
01:08:15.970 --> 01:08:19.851
gynecologic cancer risk should be

1130
01:08:19.891 --> 01:08:23.550
managed. So the high-risk gene carriers are basically getting their

1131
01:08:23.590 --> 01:08:27.271
hysterectomy and bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy at age 40.

1132
01:08:28.050 --> 01:08:31.730
For MSH6 carriers that, again, have a high endometrial

1133
01:08:31.790 --> 01:08:35.650
cancer risk, they really should have their hysterectomy at age 40, and the

1134
01:08:35.690 --> 01:08:39.271
oophorectomy can be potentially delayed until after menopause.

1135
01:08:39.851 --> 01:08:43.710
And for PMS2 carriers, because that risk of endometrial cancer

1136
01:08:43.910 --> 01:08:44.710
is lower

1137
01:08:45.771 --> 01:08:49.280
and doesn't arise until later in life, they can get their

1138
01:08:49.311 --> 01:08:50.670
hysterectomy and

1139
01:08:52.650 --> 01:08:54.400
ovaries out at age 50.

1140
01:08:55.910 --> 01:08:59.771
So this is thinking about Lynch syndrome at a gene-specific

1141
01:08:59.910 --> 01:09:03.840
level. But how about reduced penetrance genes within Lynch syndrome?

1142
01:09:04.250 --> 01:09:05.750
Oh, sorry, but before I get to that,

1143
01:09:06.590 --> 01:09:10.250
I did just want to highlight a few other difficulties that we

1144
01:09:10.311 --> 01:09:13.230
have when thinking about single variants in Lynch syndrome.

1145
01:09:13.931 --> 01:09:17.870
And that is that the cancer risk estimates that we

1146
01:09:17.910 --> 01:09:18.610
get, although we

1147
01:09:19.851 --> 01:09:23.431
give people, say, a colon cancer risk estimate or endometrial cancer risk

1148
01:09:23.510 --> 01:09:27.311
estimate, these risks do vary quite substantially,

1149
01:09:27.450 --> 01:09:30.250
even among single variants within Lynch syndrome.

1150
01:09:30.950 --> 01:09:34.830
So this is data looking at colorectal cancer risk on MSH2

1151
01:09:34.891 --> 01:09:38.510
carriers. And what you can see here is that over a lifetime, there's pretty

1152
01:09:38.610 --> 01:09:42.250
broad confidence intervals with this colorectal cancer risk

1153
01:09:42.330 --> 01:09:45.950
estimate. But this is colorectal cancer risk for one

1154
01:09:45.990 --> 01:09:49.510
specific MSH2 variant across many, many

1155
01:09:49.630 --> 01:09:53.330
families. And what you can see here is that even for this one variant, the

1156
01:09:53.391 --> 01:09:57.330
confidence intervals for cumulative colorectal cancer

1157
01:09:57.410 --> 01:10:00.670
risk are equally as broad, even for this single variant.

1158
01:10:02.290 --> 01:10:06.270
And interestingly, when you look at an individual's

1159
01:10:07.590 --> 01:10:11.570
risk of colorectal cancer for all MSH2

1160
01:10:11.610 --> 01:10:15.450
carriers, you likely have a population of MSH2 carriers

1161
01:10:15.490 --> 01:10:19.190
where their colon cancer risk essentially is population

1162
01:10:19.230 --> 01:10:22.590
risk. We don't know how to identify these people, but

1163
01:10:22.630 --> 01:10:26.470
certainly, this is the case. We see older

1164
01:10:26.510 --> 01:10:30.470
individuals who have had Lynch syndrome their whole life that really have not had

1165
01:10:30.490 --> 01:10:34.250
any cancer. And we see a population for this single

1166
01:10:34.450 --> 01:10:37.790
specific MSH2 variant where also there's likely some

1167
01:10:37.830 --> 01:10:38.490
individuals

1168
01:10:39.390 --> 01:10:41.830
that have a very low colorectal cancer risk.

1169
01:10:42.170 --> 01:10:44.770
But then at the same time, you have individuals

1170
01:10:45.830 --> 01:10:49.670
amongst all MSH2 carriers in this one particular variant who

1171
01:10:49.730 --> 01:10:53.330
have a near 100% risk of developing colorectal cancer.

1172
01:10:53.350 --> 01:10:57.210
And so even for this one particular variant, you have this wide

1173
01:10:57.290 --> 01:10:59.910
range of cancer risk that is possible.

1174
01:11:01.630 --> 01:11:05.170
So when we think about the reduced penetrance variants in Lynch syndrome, there

1175
01:11:05.190 --> 01:11:07.450
have been a few of them that have been described.

1176
01:11:08.470 --> 01:11:12.130
I'll point out a couple of them. This particular MLH1

1177
01:11:12.650 --> 01:11:13.070
variant,

1178
01:11:14.390 --> 01:11:18.290
it's a missense variant that's classified in ClinVar, and this

1179
01:11:18.330 --> 01:11:21.030
is a messy classification that leads to a lot of

1180
01:11:22.930 --> 01:11:24.910
difficulties with management of these individuals.

1181
01:11:24.950 --> 01:11:28.010
But you have one lab calling it a pathogenic

1182
01:11:28.890 --> 01:11:32.300
low penetrance variant, one calling it a likely pathogenic variant,

1183
01:11:32.750 --> 01:11:35.470
10 calling it a VUS, and one calling it a likely benign.

1184
01:11:35.550 --> 01:11:39.530
So, getting one of these particular variants

1185
01:11:40.210 --> 01:11:43.610
is very messy for clinicians.

1186
01:11:44.690 --> 01:11:48.430
This other MLH1 variant down here at the bottom was just recently published

1187
01:11:48.470 --> 01:11:52.130
on by Dan Buchanan and his group in Australia, but it's really still

1188
01:11:52.170 --> 01:11:54.510
globally classified as a VUS in ClinVar.

1189
01:11:55.410 --> 01:11:59.050
But the one that I'll talk a little bit more in more detail about is this

1190
01:11:59.070 --> 01:12:02.050
particular MSH6 missense variant.

1191
01:12:02.130 --> 01:12:05.889
And this one, if you look in ClinVar, basically all labs call it

1192
01:12:05.930 --> 01:12:09.730
pathogenic or likely pathogenic, but now you have one lab that's calling it

1193
01:12:09.830 --> 01:12:12.310
a likely pathogenic low penetrance variant.

1194
01:12:12.780 --> 01:12:16.190
And we presented some data on this in a collaboration with

1195
01:12:16.430 --> 01:12:20.330
University of Chicago and one of the genetic testing labs

1196
01:12:20.390 --> 01:12:24.090
at the CGA meeting last year, but I'll go through a little bit about what we

1197
01:12:24.170 --> 01:12:24.550
found.

1198
01:12:26.170 --> 01:12:30.070
So what we found was we looked at over a million individuals

1199
01:12:30.090 --> 01:12:33.350
who had, had hereditary cancer testing at a commercial lab.

1200
01:12:34.110 --> 01:12:37.910
Of these, about 3,000 had an MSH6 variant that

1201
01:12:37.950 --> 01:12:41.190
was found, and of the MSH6 carriers, about

1202
01:12:41.450 --> 01:12:45.010
4% had this particular MSH6

1203
01:12:45.250 --> 01:12:46.650
missense variant.

1204
01:12:47.590 --> 01:12:51.170
When you look at these cancer rates amongst these individuals,

1205
01:12:51.590 --> 01:12:55.490
those that had this particular missense MSH6 variant,

1206
01:12:55.930 --> 01:12:59.730
there were lower rates of most cancers, like colorectal cancer and uterine

1207
01:12:59.810 --> 01:13:03.610
cancer, compared to the group of all MSH6

1208
01:13:03.690 --> 01:13:07.210
carriers. And a larger percentage of these individuals were

1209
01:13:07.250 --> 01:13:09.890
unaffected by any Lynch syndrome cancer.

1210
01:13:10.650 --> 01:13:14.550
And when you try to translate this then into subsequent risks,

1211
01:13:15.390 --> 01:13:19.210
what we can see here is that the dark bars here are this MSH6

1212
01:13:19.710 --> 01:13:23.450
missense variant. And what you can see is that there's really not any statistically

1213
01:13:23.570 --> 01:13:27.430
increased risk of any Lynch syndrome cancer that we

1214
01:13:27.470 --> 01:13:29.210
found for this particular variant.

1215
01:13:30.130 --> 01:13:33.950
Whereas if you look at for all MSH6 pathogenic variants, colorectal,

1216
01:13:34.070 --> 01:13:37.670
ovarian, and uterine cancer are all increased as expected.

1217
01:13:38.210 --> 01:13:42.190
And importantly, when thinking about management for uterine cancer

1218
01:13:42.270 --> 01:13:46.090
risk, it was significantly lower for carriers of this

1219
01:13:46.210 --> 01:13:50.086
MSH6 missense variant.So we

1220
01:13:50.106 --> 01:13:53.106
think that this data -- hopefully this paper will come out in the

1221
01:13:53.806 --> 01:13:57.506
next six months or so. But we think that this particular variant

1222
01:13:57.566 --> 01:14:01.106
truly is a reduced penetrance Lynch syndrome

1223
01:14:01.186 --> 01:14:04.026
variant. And so how do we manage these individuals

1224
01:14:04.126 --> 01:14:07.866
clinically? So I think from a colonoscopy standpoint,

1225
01:14:08.326 --> 01:14:12.036
what you could consider doing is extending to the longest

1226
01:14:12.086 --> 01:14:15.906
interval that our guidelines will allow for colonoscopy, which would be

1227
01:14:15.966 --> 01:14:19.896
every three years. Most people in the field are not

1228
01:14:19.946 --> 01:14:23.486
using a three-year interval, so that would be extending the interval for colon

1229
01:14:23.546 --> 01:14:26.546
cancer screening for these individuals.

1230
01:14:26.566 --> 01:14:30.326
The gynecologic risk becomes much more difficult

1231
01:14:30.626 --> 01:14:34.306
to think about. And so potential options would be, since that

1232
01:14:34.346 --> 01:14:38.206
risk seems remarkably lower, do you defer hysterectomy until age

1233
01:14:38.286 --> 01:14:39.986
50 and potentially perform

